After the Liberal International Order
Cambridge — Many analysts believe that the liberal international order came to an end with China's rise and the election of U.S. President Donald Trump.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he make efforts to revive it?
Perhaps the result isn't like that, but he must find some alternative.
Critics are right to point out that the American order after 1945 was neither inherently global nor always very free.
It excluded more than half of the world, including the Soviet bloc and China, while incorporating many authoritarian countries.
American hegemony is always exaggerated.
Nevertheless, the most powerful countries must take the lead in creating global public goods, or they will not be provided — and Americans will also suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example of this.
A practical goal for the Biden administration should be to establish an international system based on rules, with different member states participating in handling various issues.
Would China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and the 21st century, both countries were unable to balance American power, while the United States pursued its commitment to freedom values above sovereignty.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without ever obtaining approval from the United Nations Security Council.
It also supports a 2005 UN General Assembly resolution on the "responsibility to protect," aimed at safeguarding citizens from their own governments' brutal treatment — a principle the United States later used in 2011 to justify bombing Libya in order to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as the arrogance of post-Cold War Americans—for instance, when the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately resulted in a regime change, leaving Russia and China feeling deceived—while defenders of the operation describe it as the natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
In any case, the growing power of China and Russia more strictly limits the actions of liberal interventionism.
So what's left then?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty enshrined in the United Nations Charter, which stipulates that states may only wage war in self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, it has been very rare for a country to occupy the territory of a neighboring country by force, and whenever such actions occur, they usually result in high costs due to sanctions (as seen in the case of Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
In addition, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in countries in crisis, while political cooperation has successfully curbed the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of rule-based order remains critically important.
Specifically regarding economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Long before the pandemic, China's hybrid form of state capitalism had already supported an unfair mercantilist model that distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will lead to the decoupling of global supply chains, especially in situations where national security is threatened.
Although China has complained about the United States blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the U.S. stance is consistent with its claims of sovereignty.
After all, China has blocked the operations of Google, Facebook, and Twitter within its borders for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
At the same time, despite the current crisis, cooperation in key financial areas remains very strong.
On the contrary, interdependence in the ecological field creates insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereignty, as the threats transcend national borders.
No matter how much economic globalization encounters setbacks, environmental globalization will continue, as it follows biological and physical laws, which are unaffected by contemporary geopolitical logic.
The above-mentioned issues threaten everyone, but no single country is capable of solving them independently.
Power also possesses so-called positive-sum dimensions in issues such as the 2019 COVID-19 pandemic and climate change.
Under such premises, merely thinking about exercising power over others is insufficient.
We must also think from the dimension of exercising power in conjunction with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization are helpful to us and to others.
Since Nixon met with Mao in 1972, despite differences in ideology, this has not affected cooperation between China and the United States.
The challenge Biden faces is whether the United States and China can cooperate in producing global public goods while simultaneously competing in traditional areas of great power rivalry.
Cyberspace is a new and important issue — because it has a transnational character in part, but is also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has been partially fragmented.
Internet speech freedom and privacy regulations can be established within democratic countries, but such regulations will not be recognized by authoritarian states.
As suggested by the Global Commission on the Stability of Cyberspace, if authoritarian regimes also wish to achieve interconnectivity, certain rules prohibiting the tampering of the fundamental structure of the internet would also be in their interests.
But when they use proxies to wage information warfare or interfere in elections (practices that violate sovereignty), norms must be reinforced through rules such as those negotiated during the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union to limit the escalation of maritime incidents (although ideological hostility remains).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly state the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrents.
Upholding the values of freedom in cyberspace does not mean that the United States unilaterally disarms itself.
On the contrary, the United States should distinguish between soft power, such as open persuasion, which is permissible, and hard power, such as secret information warfare. When the other side launches a secret information campaign, the United States is certainly required to retaliate.
Russia and China can be allowed to openly broadcast programs and radio, but secret unification actions such as manipulating social media are not permitted.
Moreover, the United States will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
Public opinion polls show that the American public hopes to avoid military intervention but does not want to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
Moreover, the public still values these principles.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the liberal international order.
The issue is whether the United States can cooperate with its core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while also working with a broader range of countries to manage international rules-based institutions necessary to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemics, cyberattacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
